If you are a current Barnard College employee, please use the internal career site to apply for this position.
Job:
Assistant Vice President, Communications
Job Summary:
Reporting to the Vice President for Strategic Communications, the Assistant Vice President, Communications helps devise and execute Barnard’s communications and marketing strategy to further the College’s historic mission of advancing women’s leadership and education. Working across the organization, the AVP develops short- and long-term plans that balance proactive storytelling with a responsiveness to the current media landscape, always with an emphasis on clear, consistent, and timely communications. The ideal candidate is able to effectively speak to multiple constituencies—students, alumnae, faculty, staff, members of the press, the general public—in service to the College and its goals. The AVP also provides public-relations counsel to Barnard leaders on an array of initiatives and emerging issues, meaning that this person is often working on high-impact, time-sensitive projects.  



The AVP is a skilled manager and oversees members of the communications team as they create and implement marketing and communications campaigns that attract top college applicants, motivate alumnae, recruit high-quality faculty and staff, and advance the institution’s overall priorities. The AVP supports the VP in team management and operations, paying special attention to processes, workflow, and the use of consistent editorial standards. As such, the ideal candidate is an adept problem-solver, an excellent writer and editor, a natural diplomat, and a savvy strategist.
Job Description:
Duties & Responsibilities:* Helps develop and implement an integrated communications and marketing plan to define Barnard’s identity, broaden awareness of its programs and priorities, and increase the visibility of the institution across key audiences;
* Devises communications strategies that incorporate multiple channels, including external, internal, media, social, executive, and owned;
* Writes and edits a variety of complex and/or sensitive communications, including press releases, talking points, media-relations materials, and executive summaries;
* Works closely with members of the national, local, and student press to accurately and effectively communicate the College’s positions and priorities;
* Participates in crisis-communications planning and response;
* Manages members of the communications team and assists VP with overall team operations, including hiring, development, and the implementation of processes;
* Liaises with academic and alumnae communications leads to ensure that outreach to these key audiences reflects the College’s overall communications strategy;
* Ensures that communications across the College adhere to Barnard’s style guide, which reflects the highest standards of writing and visual presentation;
* Performs additional duties and responsibilities as needed.


Skills, Qualifications & Requirements:
Knowledge, Skills & Abilities:* Strong problem-solving skills, editorial judgment, and tactical thinking;
* Excellent writing and editing skills and the ability to craft compelling narratives and story pitches;
* Deep contacts across the media spectrum, including print, digital, TV, and radio;
* High level of discretion, judgment and professionalism;
* Ability to interact and build relationships with a variety of constituents;
* Demonstrated success managing a team of communications/marketing professionals;
* Keen interest in local, national, and world news coverage of major events and key issues in higher education;
* Comprehensive understanding of print, digital, and social news cycles.


Qualifications:* 10 years of experience in communications, media relations, and/or marketing;
* Five years of experience managing a team in a complex enterprise;
* Experience working with New York City’s media market as well as national and international press;
* Demonstrated crisis-communications experience;
* Demonstrated ability to create and implement successful communications campaigns;
* Robust understanding of key issues in higher education.


Salary Range: $165,000 - $180,000 annually*The salary of the finalist selected for this role will be set based on a variety of factors, including but not limited to departmental budgets, qualifications, experience, education, licenses, specialty, and training. The above hiring range represents the College's good faith and reasonable estimate of the range of possible compensation at the time of posting.*
